In general, if you have <i>N</i> cards, merge sort will require <i>log<sub>2</sub>N</i> passes.  That is, the number of passes will be no greater than the base-2 logarithm of <i>N</i>.   For a deck with 16 cards, that's 4 passes. For a deck with 32 cards, that's 5 passes. And for deck with 52 cards, that would be 6 passes, because 52 is less than 2<sup>6</sup> = 64.", "rows": 1, "description": "5.Sort.3 Counting merges", "hint": "You might compare this question to the similar question we asked in the case of binary search &ndash; i.e., how many times can you divide 64 in half? ", "graders": [{"matcher": "numeric", "score": "1.0", "response": "6", "feedback": "A 64-card deck would require 6 merge sort passes to create piles of size  2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64.  

